=== Tsutsumine Shrine (Hiejima, Kadoma) ===
{{神社
 | 名称=Tsutsumine Shrine
 | 画像=[[File:堤根神社, Tsuneki Shrine, P1000227.jpg|250px]]<br />Torii
 | 所在地={{ill|lt=Osaka Prefecture|Q122723|WD=Q122723|1=Osaka Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Kadoma|Q496080|WD=Q496080|1=Kadoma, Osaka}}422 Hiejima
 | 位置={{ウィキ座標2段度分秒|34|43|9.9|N|135|35|22.3|E|region:JP}}
 | 祭神={{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Amaterasu Sumeōkami|1=UNKNOWN}}<br />{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Susanoo-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}<br />{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ōnamuchi-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}
 | 社格={{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} (small) / former {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}
 | 例祭=3rd Sunday of October
 | 地図={{Location map|Japan Osaka|label=Tsutsumine Shrine|position=bottom|width=200|mark=Shinto torii icon vermillion.svg|marksize=15|float=center|caption=}}
{{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|zoom=12|marker=religious-shinto|frame-align=center|frame-width=200|coord={{coord|34|43|9.9|N|135|35|22.3|E}}}}
}}

Its deities are {{ill|lt=Amaterasu|Q455602|WD=Q455602|lt=Amaterasu Sumeōkami|1=Amaterasu}}, {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|WD=Q272993|lt=Susanoo-no-Kami|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}}, and Ōnamuchi-no-Kami ({{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|WD=Q276944|1=Ōkuninushi}}).

The founding date is unknown, but in the cadastral register of {{ill|lt=Bunroku|Q1373039|WD=Q1373039|1=Bunroku}} 3 ({{ill|lt=1594|Q6777|WD=Q6777|1=1594}}), it appears as "Sannō-gū" serving as ujigami of Hiejima and Kuwasai villages. The "Sannō" name is thought to derive from enshrining Ōnamuchi-no-Kami. In the register of {{ill|lt=Kyōhō|Q1145048|WD=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}} 10 ({{ill|lt=1725|Q6932|WD=Q6932|1=1725}}), it appears as "Yatsurugi Daimyōjin," likely from enshrining Susanoo-no-Kami. A document from Genbun 3 ({{ill|lt=1738|Q6996|WD=Q6996|1=1738}}) says three seats were enshrined by adding Amaterasu. In the Meiji 12 "Kita-Kawachi District Shrine Property Register," the name appears as "Ryōmura Shrine," and the deity is one seat of Amaterasu. The name came from being ujigami of two villages.

In Meiji 41, it was renamed "Tsutsumine Shrine" as an alleged descendant of the Shikinaisha Tsutsumine Shrine. There is no material proving Shikinaisha status, and it is thought the claim was made to avoid {{ill|lt=shrine mergers|Q11590700|WD=Q11590700|1=Shrine Consolidation Policy}}, then actively promoted at the time; nevertheless, in August of that year it was merged into gōsha {{ill|lt=Mishima Shrine|Q11355275|WD=Q11355275|1=Mishima Shrine (Taito)}} (present 1374 Mitsushima, Kadoma). In Shōwa 21, it separated from Mishima Shrine and was restored at the old site.

